Name: Victor Wembanyama
2026 Outlook: Wembanyama has No. 1 upside in points leagues and is the clear favorite to be No. 1 in roto and category leagues. He blocked 3.8 shots and knocked down 3.1 3-pointers per game last season, in addition to notching more than a steal, giving him an unheard-of combination of more than eight combined in blocks, 3s and steals. This is in addition to his mid-20s scoring, nightly double-doubles and strong shooting percentages. Deep vein thrombosis in his right shoulder ended his second NBA campaign early, but Wembanyama has been cleared to play for 2025-26. Only 21 years old, Wembanyama still has huge upside to improve, a scary concept for his opponents and fantasy hoops managers.

Name: Nikola Jokić
2026 Outlook: Jokic has been the best fantasy producer in the NBA for the last five seasons and it hasn't been particularly close. He's coming off clearly the best fantasy season of his career, in which he notched career-highs in points, assists, steals and 3-pointers per game as part of his rounded average of a 30-point, 13-rebound, 10 assist triple-double. Jokic will reprise the same role again this season, and he's still in his prime at 30 years old, so barring injury he should remain at or near the top of fantasy hoops rankings yet again.

Name: Luka Dončić
2026 Outlook: Doncic's trade last season shifted the landscape in both the NBA and fantasy hoops. In Dallas, Doncic was the primary ball-dominant option even when Kyrie Irving was healthy, but in Los Angeles he shares the court with the still high-usage LeBron James. Doncic also dealt with injury last season that limited his output, so his upside for the Lakers isn't fully clear. The Lakers spent the offseason centering Doncic as the new face of the franchise, and they brought in players to support his skill set, but it is difficult to see Doncic getting enough volume to challenge the 33.9 PPG, 9.8 APG or 9.2 RPG he averaged in 2023-24. He's still a top-5 fantasy hoops prospect, but no longer in the conversation for the top overall pick.

Name: Shai Gilgeous-Alexander
2026 Outlook: Gilgeous-Alexander is on top of the basketball world as the reigning NBA MVP and Finals MVP, in addition to scoring champion. His situation is optimized by his role with the Thunder; he is the leading offense generator off the dribble, has teammates whose shooting helps create driving lanes for him to exploit, and has a coach that still runs plays to get him open mid-range looks. SGA set new career bests in scoring, assists and 3-pointers made last season, and at 27 years of age is just hitting his peak athletic years. Add in that he has played at least 75 games in consecutive seasons, and SGA is a viable option for the top overall pick in fantasy drafts even if he'll typically settle in more like top-3.

Name: Anthony Davis
2026 Outlook: Davis had offseason eye surgery but is expected to be ready for the start of the season, and if he's healthy his situation with the Mavericks could allow him to challenge for career-high production across the board. Davis is the primary offensive and defensive producer for the Mavericks, and with Kyrie Irving out he should get plenty of volume even as Cooper Flagg and the rest of the Mavs offense helps keep a bit of defensive pressure off him.

Name: Anthony Edwards
2026 Outlook: Edwards has improved his scoring average every season of his career, up to 27.6 PPG last season. Still only 24 years old, Edwards has a tendency to return with a new skill after every offseason. Last season, that skill was a dramatic improvement in both volume and efficiency from behind the arc. This not only leads to better statistical production, but also changes the way opposing defenses have to defend him and opens up driving lanes for his highlight-real finishing opportunities. Edwards ranked only 19th in fantasy points scoring average last season, but he played in 79 games for the third season in a row and thus scored the fifth-most fantasy points in the league. Edwards has only missed more than three games once in his five NBA seasons, and he still played 72 games that season. He has top-5 potential in 2025-26.

Name: James Harden
2026 Outlook: Harden enjoyed a career renaissance last season, turning in his best scoring season since 2021-22 with elite peripheral numbers while playing in 79 games, his most since 2016-17. The end result was Harden finishing fourth in the NBA in total fantasy points, his first top-5 finish since his days with the Rockets. The question is whether he repeat that this season? Now in his age-36 season, Harden has a game that doesn't overly rely on athleticism, with strong pick-and-roll/pop options in the frontcourt to partner with. The biggest limitations on Harden's upside may be the presence of Kawhi Leonard, who remains the No. 1 option when healthy, and the depth of the Clippers after an offseason where they brought in quite a bit of quality options.

Name: Trae Young
2026 Outlook: Young enters his age-27 season fresh off three straight seasons averaging more than 24 points and 10 assists per game. Interestingly, his scoring average has decreased four straight seasons, from 28.4 PPG in 2021-22 down to 24.2 PPG last season, while his assists average has increased every season of his career up to 11.6 APG. These trends are likely to continue this season, with the Hawks featuring finishers at every position when their starting lineup is healthy.

Name: Stephen Curry
2026 Outlook: Curry is well established as the best shooter of all-time, but the question in recent years has been his age and injury history. After averaging only 51 games played per year from 2017-18 through 2022-23, Curry has played at least 70 games in each of the last two seasons. Curry still showed signs of slippage, though, playing fewer minutes and posting some of his lowest field goal percentages of his career. This season, Curry still projects at a mid-20s scorer with strong 3-pointers and solid all-around numbers, but at 37 years old his risks lower him to a top-25 fantasy hoops prospect instead of a first rounder.

Name: Chet Holmgren
2026 Outlook: Holmgren played 82 games in 2023-24, technically his rookie season but his second season in the pros. In the season before and the season after, injuries limited Holmgren to 32 of a possible 164 games played. Thus, health and availability are the biggest question marks for Holmgren heading into this season. Holmgren's minutes dropped from 29.4 to 27.4 last season, likely due to a combination of the injury and the fact that the Thunder outscored their opponents by double-digits on a nightly basis. If Holmgren can increase his minutes over 30 this season, he has both double-double and 3.0 blocks per game upside, which could move him up into the early rounds of fantasy drafts.

Name: Giannis Antetokounmpo
2026 Outlook: Antetokounmpo remains on the short list of best fantasy producers in the NBA, coming off back-to-back seasons averaging over 30 points, 11.5 rebounds and 6.5 assists per game. Those numbers came largely with Damian Lillard as his point guard, but in 14 games without Lillard, Giannis averaged slightly more points (31.1 PPG) and almost a full 1.5 more assists (7.9 APG). With Lillard gone this season and shooting big man Myles Turner in the fold as another finisher, Antetokounmpo has even higher upside this season with an outside shot at flirting with a triple-double.

Name: Karl-Anthony Towns
2026 Outlook: Towns shined in his first season with the Knicks. His move back to the center position brought him closer to the rim on defense and led to his career-best 12.8 RPG, while on offense he remained a strong combination of efficient interior finisher and volume long-range shooter. Towns and Jalen Brunson were able to play well off each other, giving defenses two high-volume, efficient scorers that prevented opponents from focusing on either. Towns finished 11th in the NBA in both fantasy scoring average and total fantasy points last season, but two of those that finished ahead of him are out with Achilles injuries. Towns thus projects to a top-10, first-round prospect in fantasy leagues this season.

Name: Domantas Sabonis
2026 Outlook: Sabonis is well established as a top-15 fantasy hoops prospect. He finished 13th in fantasy points per game as well as total fantasy points last season. Sabonis has been the best passing center this side of Nikola Jokic for years, so last season's 6.0 APG was his lowest average since joining the Kings. Kings head coach Doug Christie played with great passing centers when he was a player, and with De'Aaron Fox traded away the Kings no longer start a pure point guard, so Sabonis could see a bounce-back in assists this season. If he stays healthy, Sabonis has top-10 fantasy upside this season.

Name: Scottie Barnes
2026 Outlook: Barnes finished just under the career-marks he established in 2023-24 in almost every category last season, but he played in five more games and thus had slightly more total fantasy points, enough to finish as top-40 fantasy option. Barnes is a do-everything producer who, at only 24 years old, still has plenty of upside to get even better. There are some question marks as to what the Raptors will look like with Brandon Ingram joining Barnes and RJ Barrett as a trio of high-scoring wings, but Barnes' versatile skill set allows him to be an impact player even if his shot volume should decrease.

Name: LeBron James
2026 Outlook: James recorded another elite fantasy hoops campaign last season despite turning 40 years old in December. He finished top-10 in the NBA in both fantasy points per game and total fantasy points, proving his continued elite status. James also played 70 games for the second straight season, the first time he's done that since he played with the Cavaliers in 2017-18. The biggest question marks for whether James can do it again are age/health concerns and the presence of Luka Doncic. James' stats dropped slightly after Doncic arrived last season, which makes sense because Doncic is a high-usage player. That said, James still averaged 23.7 PPG, 7.8 RPG and 6.7 APG in 23 games with Doncic despite playing through injury in those contests.

Name: Kevin Durant
2026 Outlook: Durant was the biggest prize of the NBA offseason, and the Rockets won his services in a trade for Jalen Green and Dillon Brooks. In season 18 of his illustrious NBA career, Durant's game is very well known. When he's on the court, he's going to score in the mid-upper 20s with six or more boards and a handful of assists per game. Durant's assists dropped the last few seasons next to Devin Booker in Phoenix, but he will be clearly the top-offensive option for a Rockets team that already needed his skill set before Fred VanVleet's ACL injury. The main question for Durant this season is health. He has only played more than 62 games in a season once since the end of the 2018-19 season, averaging only 46 games in the six seasons since.

Name: Cade Cunningham
2026 Outlook: Cunningham is coming off the healthiest campaign of his career, and by far his best. With new career-highs of in scoring, assists, 3-pointers and field goal percentage, Cunningham notched his first All Star selection and solidified himself as a fantasy first-rounder for the foreseeable future. Cunningham is only 23 years old and still improving, and his last season makes averages of 30 points and 10 assists realistically attainable. The main question with Cunningham is health. While he played 70 out of 82 games last season, in his first three he only played 138 of a possible 246 games.

Name: Donovan Mitchell
2026 Outlook: Mitchell is the Cavaliers' MVP, but his box score production has gone down in each of the last two seasons because the team around him has gotten stronger. Mitchell can still ramp up to 30-point games when needed, typically in the playoffs and/or when his teammate are injured, but the Cavaliers were so successful last season that Mitchell only needed to play a career-low 31 MPG and thus his volume dropped accordingly. He is still a top-25 fantasy prospect, but his days of returning first round value are likely done as long as his team is playing so well.

Name: Tyrese Maxey
2026 Outlook: Maxey took over as the leading fantasy producer for the 76ers last season due to Joel Embiid's injuries, but Maxey's season was also cut short at only 52 games due to his own combination of injuries. When healthy, Maxey is an elite scorer with solid peripheral numbers in categories like assists and 3-pointers. Last season, he ranked top-15 in the league in fantasy scoring average. With fellow All Stars Embiid and Paul George consistently dealing with injuries, the 24-year old Maxey has the opportunity to continue to develop and even increase his production this season.

Name: LaMelo Ball
2026 Outlook: Ball is one of the most talented young guards in the NBA, an All-Star coming off averages of 25.2 PPG, 7.4 APG, 4.9 RPG and 3.8 3PG. His biggest issue is availability: in five NBA seasons, Ball has only played more than 51 games once. He has combined to play only 105 of a possible 246 games in the last three seasons. Ball is still only 24 years old and still getting better, but the Hornets have also brought in plenty of perimeter depth options this offseason to prepare in case he has availability issues again. Fantasy managers would be wise to do the same.

Name: De'Aaron Fox
2026 Outlook: Fox was traded to the Spurs last season, and after signing a max contract extension this offseason he will be one of their pillars for the foreseeable future. Fox has always been a great offense-producer, and his two-man game with Victor Wembanyama has the potential to be one of the best in the league. Fox's scoring volume likely decreases with the Spurs, where he'll be playing off Wembanyama with a squad full of other plus perimeter scorers. If healthy, he should maintain his status as a top-30 fantasy producer this season.

Name: Jaren Jackson Jr.
2026 Outlook: Jackson suffered a turf toe injury and had surgery in July that was expected to keep him out at least three months. He may be ready for the start of the season, but it's also possible the injury keeps him sidelined. Jackson played in 74 games last season, but that was only the second time in his career he played more than 66 games, so health has been a consistent issue. But when he's on the court, Jackson is one of the rare players that averages solidly more than a 3-pointer, blocked shot and steal per game. He has also scored more than 22 PPG in two straight seasons, and with Desmond Bane traded away is poised to be the second high-volume scorer for the Grizzlies alongside Ja Morant again in this campaign.

Name: Amen Thompson
2026 Outlook: Thompson was one of the breakout stars of last season, particularly after he earned a spot in the Rockets' starting lineup. In 42 games as a starter, he averaged 16.0 PPG, 9.2 RPG, 4.9 APG, 1.7 SPG and 1.6 BPG. Still only 22 years old, Thompson has plenty of upside to improve on those numbers this season. He will have more perimeter responsibilities in 2025-26 with Fred VanVleet injured and both Jalen Green and DIllon Brookis traded for Kevin Durant. Thompson has top-25 fantasy hoops upside this season.

Name: Derrick White
2026 Outlook: White is coming off the best season of his career, establishing new career-highs in scoring, rebounds and 3-pointers per game as the third option on the Celtics. With Jayson Tatum out for the season and Jrue Holiday traded to Portland, White could have more responsibility for the Celtics this season. He will be relied upon to not only knock down open looks, but to also create more for himself and teammates. His scoring and assists could both see an uptick this season, moving him further into impact territory.

Name: Devin Booker
2026 Outlook: Booker is coming off a season where he finished top-25 in the NBA in fantasy point scoring average but top-15 in total fantasy points because he was able to play in 75 games. That was Booker's highest game-total since 2017, and his fewest games missed since 2021. Booker is a consistently high-level producer, but with Kevin Durant and Bradley Beal both traded away this offseason it could set the stage for Booker's highest usage in his career. Booker is poised to be the starting point guard for the Suns this season, tabbed to be the primary creator for both himself and his teammates. If he stays healthy, he has the potential to set new career-highs across the board.

Name: Myles Turner
2026 Outlook: Turner joined the Bucks this offseason after a stellar run with the Pacers. In his last three seasons, Turner has averaged 16.9 PPG, 7.0 RPG, 2.1 BPG and 1.7 3PG. He is both an offensive and defensive upgrade over what the Bucks got from Brook Lopez last season, which is good for both Turner and his teammates this season. Turner should continue to get wide-open looks from downtown as teams focus on slowing Giannis Anteotokounmo in the paint, and he should have plenty of shot-blocking opportunities on a Bucks defense that likes to funnel opponents to their rim protectors in the paint. Conversely, Turner's ability to stretch the floor on offense and correct mistakes on defense should improve the peripheral numbers of the other Bucks starters.

Name: Jalen Brunson
2026 Outlook: Brunson is coming off his third straight elite campaign since joining the Knicks, and proved he could not only coexist with but also thrive next to star center Karl-Anthony Towns. Brunson notched career-best marks in assists and steals last season, with his second-best scoring and 3-point shooting numbers. He only played 65 games last season, only the second time in the last five seasons he missed more than four games. Brunson ranked 22nd in the league in fantasy scoring average last season, and has top-20 upside if he remains healthy this season.

Name: Ja Morant
2026 Outlook: Morant remains the franchise player for the Grizzlies, but availability remains the biggest question mark in his output. Through a combination of injuries and suspension, Morant has only played 59 of a possible 164 games in the last two seasons and averaged 44 games played over the past four seasons. Morant remains one of the most dynamic, athletic guards in the NBA and has improved as both a shooter and a distributor in recent seasons. He ranked just outside the top-40 in fantasy points per game last season, but if he is healthy and consistently in the lineup this season he has top-25 upside in fantasy leagues.

Name: Evan Mobley
2026 Outlook: Mobley is the NBA Defensive Player of the Year and is also coming off a career-year as both a scorer and 3-point shooter. His production was particularly impressive because he did it on a career-low 30.5 MPG. The Cavaliers team was so strong as a unit that none of the individuals needed to play heavy minutes. If Mobley were still playing the 34+ MPG of his first two seasons, he would likely average a 20-10 double-double. He may anyway, since he's still only 24 years old and getting better. Either way, he's a top-25 fantasy prospect this season.

Name: Jalen Williams
2026 Outlook: Williams has improved every season of his NBA career, surpassing the 20/5/5 threshold with almost two 3-pointers and more than two blocks + steals per game last season. He is both a strong slasher and a strong shooter from deep, particularly via the spot-up, and working against defenses focused on stopping Shai Gilgeous-Alexander lets Williams get consistent looks against imbalanced units. Still only 24 years old, there is every reason to expect J-Dub to continue to improve into even more of an impact fantasy player this season.

Name: Desmond Bane
2026 Outlook: In his last few years with the Grizzlies, Bane developed into one of the better all-around shooter-scorer-playmakers on the wing in the NBA. He first showed he could be a primary scorer when injuries and suspension kept Ja Morant out of the lineup, but he has since proven he can produce even when in the lineup with other volume scorers. This will serve him well in Orlando, where he will be playing next to two strong offensive producers in the frontcourt in Paolo Banchero and Franz Wagner. Bane's ability to stretch the floor should open things up for Banchero and Wagner to create, while simultaneously their presence should get Bane more open looks. His efficiency could increase in Orlando, but his scoring volume is likely capped by his two talented teammates.

Name: Cooper Flagg
2026 Outlook: Flagg is one of the more anticipated rookies of this generation and should be an impact player at the NBA level right away. He's got excellent size for a small forward, a versatile game at both ends of the court that is strong from the rim to outside the 3-point line, and a competitive mindset that will serve him well against the highest levels of competition. With Kyrie Irving out for the first half of the season, Flagg projects to play off Anthony Davis as a primary scorer, secondary offense-initiator and plus defender. He should be both a high-volume and a high-efficiency producer, and a multi-category guy with no real weakness in category leagues.

Name: Jamal Murray
2026 Outlook: Murray is coming off arguably his best season as a pro, posting a career-high 21.4 PPG and 1.4 SPG while playing more games (67) than he has since 2018-19. Availability has been an issue for Murray, who has only averaged 60 games over the past five seasons. But his per-game production could be on an upswing with the offseason trade of Michael Porter. Jr. Both were instant-offense types, so in the same offense they had to take turns in a way Murray likely won't with Porter's replacement Cameron Johnson. Murray plays a mean two-man game with Nikola Jokic, and that will remain the basis for his production this season.

Name: Paolo Banchero
2026 Outlook: Banchero was the NBA Rookie of the Year in 2022-23, then improved across the board in his second season and seemed poised to take the league by storm in year 3 before injuries sidelined him for half the season. He still showed improvement as a shooter and scorer, getting up to 25.9 PPG and 1.9 3PG, but didn't make the leap that some expected. That expected explosion could be on tap for this season, though, with Banchero fully healthy and the addition of Desmond Bane on the wing. Bane is an elite, volume 3-point shooter that will force opposing defenses to respect his shot and open up the paint for Banchero and Franz Wagner to operate.

Name: Bam Adebayo
2026 Outlook: Adebayo has been metronome consistent for the past five seasons, notching within decimal points of his averages of 19.1 PPG, 9.7 RPG, 4.0 AGP, 1.2 SPG and 0.8 BPG every season. Last season he started playing more power forward to allow for dual-big lineups with Kel'el Ware, and this led to Adebayo setting a new career mark with a 3-pointer per game as well. Adebayo has played in 71 or more games in three straight seasons, and his consistent availability has allowed him to finish in the top-20 in total fantasy points even though he is only top-40 in fantasy points per game.

Name: Brandon Miller
2026 Outlook: Miller enters his third season with massive breakout potential for the Hornets. Before a wrist injury cut his season short in January, he averaged 21.0 PPG, 4.9 RPG, 3.6 APG, 1.1 SPG and 3.9 3PG. That’s elite fantasy production. The former No. 2 overall pick has improved as a passer and slasher, and the Hornets will lean on him heavily as a primary scorer. Efficiency will be the key swing factor, but if he takes a leap there, Miller could push for his first All-Star nod. He’s a priority target at his average draft position with top-30 upside.

Name: Paul George
2026 Outlook: George was the 76ers' big free offseason acquisition in 2024-25, but managed only 41 games due to injury. George has already re-injured his knee this offseason, requiring arthroscopic surgery that leaves his availability for the start of the season in doubt. In the 41 games George did play last season, the combination of nagging injury and productive teammates limited George to a 10-season low of 16.2 PPG. It isn't clear what his upside might be on these 76ers at this juncture of his career. Maybe a best-case scenario would have him as a top-30 producer per game but, with a high risk to be unavailable at any given time, that lowers his overall value to closer to top-75.

Name: Alperen Sengun
2026 Outlook: Sengun has turned in consecutive elite-production seasons, earning his first All Star berth and averaging a double-double for the first time in his last campaign. In that span, he averaged a rounded 20 points, 10 rebounds and 5 assists with just over a steal and just under a block per game. While the second leading scorer, Sengun was arguably the primary offense contributor for the Rockets last season. He should get even more opportunity this season, because with Kevin Durant replacing Jalen Green as the leading scorer, Sengun will be operating against less-focused defenses. Sengun also likely gets more creation opportunity this season with point guard Fred VanVleet injured.

Name: Miles Bridges
2026 Outlook: Bridges has been a metronome in his last three seasons, producing within decimal points of his averages of 20.5 PPG, 7.3 RPG, 2.1 3PG and 3.7 APG in all three seasons. Nothing changes this season; Bridges still projects as the primary frontcourt scorer that can thrive when the offense runs through him. If anything, the Hornets traded away centers with some offensive ability and replaced them with role players, so Bridges could have even more responsibility this season.

Name: Jaylen Brown
2026 Outlook: Brown has the game to be a No. 1 scorer, but has been cast as the second option on the Celtics behind Jayson Tatum. With Tatum out this season due to a torn Achilles, Brown is positioned to take over. During the past two seasons, Brown has averaged 22.2 PPG in 120 games with Tatum in the lineup and 26.8 PPG in the 13 games Tatum missed. The Celtics still have good scoring in their backcourt, but they have a dearth of proven scoring ability in the frontcourt. Based on opportunity, Brown's scoring could increase even beyond his typical non-Tatum numbers.

Name: Jalen Johnson
2026 Outlook: Johnson was in the midst of a career season when he tore his labrum and found himself sidelined. But in the 36 games he played, he set new-career highs in all five counting categories, averaging 19.9 PPG, 5.0 APG and at least one steal, block and 3-pointer per game. Johnson's do-everything style fits well alongside Trae Young's offense creation, and this season they will look to form a Big Three with newcomer Kristaps Porzingis. Johnson is still only 23 years old, so if he's healthy he should continue to improve in his fifth season.

Name: Jalen Green
2026 Outlook: Green was the leading scorer on a balanced if offensively-challenged Rockets team last season, but this offseason he was dealt to the Suns as the centerpiece of a Kevin Durant trade. While Green projects as the second option for the Suns behind Devin Booker, he has higher upside in Phoenix than he did in Houston. The Suns have a dearth of scoring options in the starting lineup, so Green should get as many shots as he can handle out of those left behind by Kevin Durant. In addition, opponents will be focused more on stopping Booker, giving Green the chance to work against more imbalanced defenses than he typically saw with the Rockets.

Name: Walker Kessler
2026 Outlook: Kessler has been a per-minute standout that is slowly building up his MPG. For his career, Kessler has averaged 13.4 points, 13.2 rebounds and 3.4 blocks per 36 minutes. Last season he played a career-high 30.0 MPG, but also a career-low 58 games. The end result had Kessler finish in the top-60 in fantasy points scoring average, but barely in the top-75 in total fantasy points. Kessler is only 24 years old and still improving, but he also has some difficulties playing against small-ball lineups and now has veteran pure-center Jusuf Nurkic as his backup as opposed to the departed John Collins, who also plays power forward. These factors could limit his minutes. Still, Kessler has top-50 upside this season.

Name: Nikola Vucevic
2026 Outlook: In all four full seasons in Chicago, Vucevic has averaged right at 18 points, just under 11 rebounds and just over 3 assists with just under a block and steal, about 1.5 3-pointers and 50%/80% from the field and the free throw line. Vucevic is 35 years old this season, but he plays 70+ games pretty much every season and is a reliable performer in the first three or four rounds of fantasy drafts.

Name: Kristaps Porzingis
2026 Outlook: After playing a career-low 42 games last season, Porzingis was traded from Boston to Atlanta this offseason. He has averaged at least 19.5 PPG in seven straight seasons, spanning four different teams, so when he's healthy we can expect that to continue this season. Porzingis' health is always the question mark; he has played more than 57 games in a season only once since 2017-18. But when he's on the court, Porzingis' ability to be the pick-and-roll/pop finisher with consistent 3-point range should make him ideal partner with Trae Young.

Name: Dejounte Murray
2026 Outlook: Murray tore his right Achilles tendon at the end of January, 2025. There are reports that estimate he could return to NBA action about a year later, in January of 2026. If so, he would likely face minutes restrictions early and have to build up his stamina in game action so temper expectations out the gate. But once up to speed, Murray has excellent upside as an all-around producer. The Pelicans brought in point guard talent this offseason, trading for Jordan Poole and drafting Jeremiah Fears with the No. 7 overall pick in the NBA draft, so Murray could face competition for playing time. But when healthy, he is the best guard on the team so the expectation is he will eventually settle into his starter role.

Name: Pascal Siakam
2026 Outlook: Siakam averaged more than 20 PPG for the sixth straight season, but his 20.2 PPG last campaign were down from the 22.8 PPG he averaged over his last four seasons with the Raptors. His assists were also down, from 4.8 APG his last four season in Toronto to 3.4 last season. Conversely, his efficiency was much better, as he shot over 51.9% from the field last season -- up from 47.2%. This all makes sense because Siakam was the main option in Toronto but was playing off Tyrese Haliburton in Indiana. With Haliburton out for the season, Siakam's numbers this season could resemble his Toronto days.

Name: Kawhi Leonard
2026 Outlook: Leonard missed the majority of last season as he recovered from an injury suffered the previous season, playing the third-fewest games (37) of his career. Leonard has dealt with injury management every season since 2017-18, averaging only 42 games played per year in those eight seasons. With that said, he has typically played between 52 and 68 games during that stretch. Not enough to be the first round talent his per-game production suggests, but at least enough for him to produce impact totals. He enters this season with top-50 fantasy scoring upside in total, but between load management and risk of further injury, it is very risky to draft Leonard before the middle rounds of fantasy drafts.

Name: Josh Hart
2026 Outlook: Hart returned top-40 value in fantasy scoring average, but top-20 value in total fantasy points last season. His unique, do-it-all style allows him to contribute positively in almost every category with no real weaknesses in any. This makes him valuable in both points and category leagues, and since his production outpaces his name recognition, Hart can typically be selected lower than he should be in fantasy drafts. One note of caution, it has been announced that Hart will play with a splint on his finger this season after re-aggravating an injury that he had surgery on in July. Hart has played at least 76 games in three straight seasons, but the splint could impact his production this season.

Name: Rudy Gobert
2026 Outlook: Gobert's numbers have slid a bit in recent seasons, but he remains a nightly double-double with more than two blocks + steals per game on very high field goal percentage at low volume. He's a finisher on offense and a shot-blocker/rebounder on defense. Gobert blocked only 1.4 shots per game last season, tied for his lowest mark since his rookie season, but the last time he did that (2022-23) he bounced back with 2.1 BPG the next season. Gobert still played 33.2 MPG last season, but he could conceivably begin to lose minutes to the combination of Naz Reid and Julius Randle, both of whom signed large multi-year extensions in the offseason.

Name: Jordan Poole
2026 Outlook: Poole bounced back from a down campaign in 2023-24 to turn in a career-effort last season. He notched career-best marks in scoring, assists, steals, blocks and 3-pointers in his last season with the Wizards that led to him getting the opportunity to run the Pelicans this season. The Pelicans start two defensive-minded players in Herbert Jones and Yves Missi, so Poole should get as much offensive volume as he can handle. Zion Williamson also plays a lot of point-forward, which should allow Poole to run some plays off the ball and get consistent spot-up scoring looks as well.

Name: Joel Embiid
2026 Outlook: Embiid was the MVP of the NBA just three seasons ago, but injuries have limited him to only 58 of a possible 164 games in the two seasons since. The injuries were so bad last season that even in the 19 games Embiid played, he was limited to multi-year lows in just about every counting category. It was the first time in his career Embiid failed to block at least one shot per game, and the first time since his rookie season he managed only single-digit rebounds. Embiid may be healthy enough to play when this season starts, but his knee issues are chronic so it is difficult to trust he will be available for even half the season. Drafting him in fantasy leagues indicates a willingness to risk not having him available at all in exchange for the reward of his historic upside if/when he is able to play.

Name: Brook Lopez
2026 Outlook: Lopez joins the Clippers on a two-year deal, giving them a proven veteran presence behind starting center Ivica Zubac. At 37, Lopez remains productive, averaging 13.0 PPG, 5.0 RPG, 1.9 BPG, and 37% from 3-point land last season with the Bucks while playing 31.8 MPG. He offers floor spacing, rim protection and the flexibility to pair with Zubac for big lineups. Lopez’s upside comes in scoring and 3s off the bench, but minutes may be limited given Zubac’s role. Fantasy managers should view him as a low-risk bench/streaming option with occasional big games.

Name: Franz Wagner
2026 Outlook: Wagner took significant strides as a scorer and playmaker last season, contributing to his career-high marks in all six fantasy hoops counting categories. He got added responsibility due to all the injuries in the Magic lineup, but he took advantage of those opportunities and showed he can be an efficient high-volume scorer and distributor on a consistent basis. The Magic expect to have Paolo Banchero healthy this season, and also traded for excellent 3-point shooter Desmond Bane, so Wagner could be part of an offensive big three. That might cap his production slightly, but it also means he is more often operating against imbalanced defenses and likely getting more high-percentage looks.

Name: Josh Giddey
2026 Outlook: Giddey finished last season with the best extended run of his career. Starting Feb. 20, he was a decimal-point away from averaging a 20-point triple-double over his last 19 games. The Bulls rewarded Giddey with a huge contract extension this offseason, and the plan seems to be to build around him as the main cog moving forward. If he continues this season like he finished last, he has top-20 fantasy hoops upside.

Name: Austin Reaves
2026 Outlook: Reaves finished with a top-50 fantasy hoops season by average and top-35 by totals last season, fueled by career-best marks of 20.2 PPG, 5.8 APG, 4.5 RPG, 2.7 3PG and 1.1 SPG. Reaves is just reaching his athletic peak at age 27, but with the moves the Lakers have made it's hard to see him replicating his production this season. With Luka Doncic and LeBron James as the main offense-generators, as well as new additions Deandre Ayton and Marcus Smart requiring minutes and shots, Reaves could take a small step back in overall production. However, he has played in 155 of a possible 164 games the last two seasons, and that level of reliability could help him maintain middle/early-middle round fantasy draft status even if his per-game numbers dip slightly.

Name: Coby White
2026 Outlook: White is the scoring half of the Bulls' backcourt. Last season, the Bulls officially moved on from the DeMar DeRozan/Zach LaVine era, and built their offense around do-everything Josh Giddey and the shooter and scorer, White. In his last 25 games of the season, White averaged 25 PPG, over 4 assists, over 4 rebounds and almost 3 3-pointers per game. He has the upside to do that for the season, which makes him worth considering in the early-middle rounds of fantasy drafts.

Name: Mikal Bridges
2026 Outlook: Bridges bounced back from a slow start to his first season with the Knicks to turn in a positive campaign. His scoring responsibility is less on the deep Knicks than it was on the Nets, but he still gets enough volume and open shots to score in the upper teens with over two 3-pointers per game on 50% shooting from the field. Bridges' best ability remains his availability. He has never missed a game in his seven-season NBA career, even playing 83 games in the campaign when he was traded mid-season.

Name: CJ McCollum
2026 Outlook: The 34-year-old McCollum is a veteran lead guard on a very young, rebuilding Wizards squad. This sometimes leads to the older player losing minutes to his younger counterparts, but sometimes we see the vet maintain his minutes as he teaches the youngsters how to win. It isn't clear yet what his role will be with the Wizards, and he is also on an expiring contract that could potentially see him moved this season. Still, McCollum has averaged at least 20 points in 10 straight seasons, so if he does get starter minutes he should continue to put points on the board. The uncertainty drops him to a late-mid/late round prospect in fantasy drafts.

Name: Lauri Markkanen
2026 Outlook: Markkanen signed a big contract extension in 2024, but last season injuries and puzzling rotations led to his lowest minutes and therefore lowest volume production in his time with the Jazz. Markkanen also played a career-low 47 games in 2024-25, below his norm even though he's only averaged 56 games played per season during his career. Markkanen is in his athletic peak at 28 years old, and he is nominally still the franchise player in Utah, but the team is very young and rebuilding so there is some question as to his role this season. He still has the top-50 fantasy hoops upside he demonstrated in his first season with the Jazz, but the question marks might push him more into the middle/late-middle rounds of fantasy drafts.

Name: Brandon Ingram
2026 Outlook: Ingram played in only 18 games last season, and didn't see the court at all after the Raptors traded for him. With the Pelicans, Ingram had established himself as an easy 20/5/5 guy that tended to surpass those thresholds in each of points, rebounds and assists on a yearly basis. He joins a Raptors squad with plus scorers across the starting five and another frontcourt player in Scottie Barnes that replicates some of his point-forward abilities, so it isn't clear how that will affect Ingram's production in his new role. The bigger question is health, where Ingram has not played more than 64 games since his rookie season back in 2016-17. If healthy, Ingram has top-50 fantasy hoops upside, but with his history it is risky to draft him before the late-middle rounds.

Name: P.J. Washington
2026 Outlook: Washington enters his second full season with Dallas after signing a four-year extension, and is another option in the stacked Mavericks frontcourt featuring Anthony Davis, Cooper Flagg, Dereck Lively II and Daniel Gafford. The 27-year-old averaged 14.7 PPG, 7.8 RPG, 2.3 APG, 1.1 SPG and 1.1 BPG last season while shooting 45.3% from the floor and 38.1% from 3-point range. Washington’s versatility makes him a two-way contributor, though minutes and usage are shared in the Mavericks deep frontcourt. A solid rotational option with points, rebounds, steals, and blocks upside, he's best used in deeper leagues or as a streamer.

Name: Zach LaVine
2026 Outlook: LaVine was traded to the Kings last mid-season and found himself in the familiar position of sharing the wing with DeMar DeRozan. LaVine took about a shot less with the Kings than he did with the Bulls in 2024-25, slightly lowering his scoring volume, but he remained a high-volume scorer with solid 3-point production (3.2 made per game). His assists and rebounds dipped in Sacramento, perhaps in part because center Domantas Sabonis is so strong in both categories, but on the whole LaVine is still very productive. LaVine played in 74 games last season, the second time in three seasons he has reached that mark, his injury history raises some question marks when it comes to his fantasy draft status.

Name: Trey Murphy III
2026 Outlook: Murphy was in the midst of a career year when a shoulder injury shut him down after only 53 games. He moved into the starting lineup and notched career-highs in all six fantasy hoops counting categories, with elite production from behind the arc. The Pelicans traded Brandon Ingram at the trade deadline, opening up Murphy to be their primary offense-creator on the wing this season. With two defensive-minded starters in Herbert Jones and Yves Missi, Murphy projects to heavy offensive volume again this season even if Zion Williamson and Jordan Poole are featured as well.

Name: Julius Randle
2026 Outlook: Randle had a slow start to his first campaign with the Timberwolves, then battled injury midseason before finally finding his level and thriving down the stretch. In his last 14 games, Randle averaged 22.1 PPG, 5.9 RPG, 4.9 APG and 1.9 3PG. Outside of the rebounding, which will likely remain attenuated on the Timberwolves frontline next to Rudy Gobert and Naz Reid, Randle's other late-season numbers resembled what he produced in his last few seasons with the Knicks and indicate what we might expect from him this season. Randle is a plus scorer in the frontcourt, and his ability to be a secondary offensive hub in the frontcourt actually works well next to franchise-player Anthony Edwards with his newly developed 3-point shot. Look for Randle to start faster this season and bounce-back to the top-50 fantasy value he used to routinely return with the Knicks.

Name: Naz Reid
2026 Outlook: Reid finished top-5 in the NBA Sixth Man of the Year vote for the second straight season after winning in 2023-24, and in that span he has averaged 13.8 PPG, 5.6 RPG, 2.2 3PG, 0.9 BPG and 0.8 SPG in 25.9 MPG. He projects to a similar role this season, providing flex-worthy fantasy production off the bench with positional starter impact when he starts for the Timberwolves. Reid is also reliable, having played at least 80 games in two straight seasons and at least 77 in three of the last four.

Name: Daniel Gafford
2026 Outlook: Gafford signed a multiyear contract extension this offseason to remain with the Mavericks long-term. However, he is still in a four-part big man rotation in Dallas that includes franchise player Anthony Davis, which will limit his minutes and opportunity. Gafford is a strong per-minute player, so he still has low double-double potential with a couple blocks even if he only gets near the 21.5 MPG he played last season. The battle for playing time caps Gafford's upside to that of a streamer in most leagues.

Name: DeMar DeRozan
2026 Outlook: DeRozan is a metronome of consistency on offense, turning in at least 21 points and 4 assists for the eighth straight time last season … a period that spans four different franchises. Even at 36 years old, there's nothing to suggest that streak will come to an end this season. DeRozan also rarely misses games, playing in 77 games last season and at least 74 games in every full-length season (e.g. not 2020 or 2021) since 2015-16. The lack of missed games helped DeRozan turn in a top-30 season by total fantasy points last season despite finishing outside of the top-50 in fantasy scoring average.

Name: OG Anunoby
2026 Outlook: The Knicks return the same starting lineup this season as last, so we have a good idea what to expect from Anunoby. He is an elite 3-and-D wing, which translated to upper-teens scoring, more than two 3-pointers for the fifth-straight season and more than two combined steals + blocks for the sixth-straight season. Anunoby played a career-high 74 games last season after averaging 52 games in the four seasons before, so if he can replicate last season's availability he projects as a plus fantasy starter.

Name: Jalen Suggs
2026 Outlook: Suggs enters the season with the Orlando Magic as the team’s defensive anchor and primary playmaker, though his availability remains a concern after knee surgery ended his 2024–25 campaign. Before the injury, he was pacing toward a career year, averaging 16.2 PPG, 3.7 APG and 1.5 SPG. With Desmond Bane joining the backcourt, Suggs’ value will lean heavily on assists, steals and defensive contributions, while outside shooting remains a limitation. Upside is high if he stays healthy, but re-injury risk could cap his impact.

Name: Zion Williamson
2026 Outlook: Williamson was limited to only 30 games last season, the fourth time in six NBA seasons he has played 30 or fewer games. His per-game production remains strong; Williamson is both a high-volume and a high-efficiency scorer from the field, and he has increased his assist average every season of his career as he has developed more into a point-forward. Williamson also turned in career-best marks in both steals and blocks, and is a threat to average at least one of both this season. But the biggest question will always be his availability. Last season he ranked 18th in fantasy points per game, so if he stays on the court he returns top-20 upside in fantasy leagues.

Name: Jalen Duren
2026 Outlook: Duren is an elite per-minute producer, averaging 16.6 points, 14.3 rebounds, 3.4 assists and 1.3 blocks per 36 minutes over the last two seasons. The issue for his fantasy production is that his minutes decreased last season, from 29.1 MPG down to 26.1 MPG last season. While some of that may be due to foul trouble, as Duren also averaged 4.2 fouls per 36 in the last two seasons, the bigger cause is probably that Isaiah Stewart is a strong backup center that also needs minutes. End result is that Duren is a walking double-double and starting caliber fantasy hoops center, but maybe not the borderline top-25 producer he'd be if he could average 36 minutes per game.

Name: D'Angelo Russell
2026 Outlook: Russell signed with the Mavericks this offseason to start while Kyrie Irving recovers from injury. Irving isn't expected back until January 2026, at earliest, which gives Russell at least half the season as the nominal starter. Russell is the perfect fit for the role the Mavs want him to play; he's a shooter-scorer at the lead guard position, and since the Mavericks will run their offense through Anthony Davis and Cooper Flagg, Russell should get more opportunity to look for his own shot as opposed to having to always play floor general. While he holds the starter role, Russell has the upside to produce closer to the 18 points, 6 assists and 3 3-pointers he averaged between 2021 and 2024 than the diminished numbers from last season.

Name: Jakob Poeltl
2026 Outlook: Poeltl played a career-high 29.6 MPG last season, which led to him setting new personal bests almost across the board. He finished decimal points shy of averaging a double-double, and for the first time averaged more than a steal and a block per game. Poeltl is still only 29 years old and at his peak, and he remains the only proven center on the Raptors' roster. He has played in just 107 of a possible 164 games in the last two seasons, but Poeltl was a top-55 players in fantasy scoring average last season and has top-50 upside this season if he stays healthy.

Name: Donte DiVincenzo
2026 Outlook: DiVincenzo has a real chance to open the season as Minnesota’s starting point guard, with Mike Conley turning 38 and likely to see a reduced role. In 10 starts last season, he averaged 14.6 PPG, 4.2 RPG, and 4.1 APG while providing strong perimeter defense. Even if he doesn’t start on opening night, he played slightly more total minutes than Conley last year, suggesting his workload could grow. DiVincenzo is better viewed as a watch-list player early in the season, with potential to become a waiver-wire pickup if his minutes climb into the 30s.

Name: Anfernee Simons
2026 Outlook: The Celtics brought Simons over this summer in the trade for Jrue Holiday, and Simons should replace Holiday in the Celtics' starting lineup. Simons is a microwave scorer: he can heat up in a hurry, and when he scores he does so in bunches. Opposing defenses will be focused more on Jaylen Brown and have to respect Derrick White's shooting, which could open up more open looks for Simons than he's used to seeing. But he'll also have to adjust to being in a more formal offense where he's not the main cog, so there could be some growing pains. If he finds his level, though, he has a great opportunity to produce for the Celtics this season with Jayson Tatum sidelined.

Name: John Collins
2026 Outlook: After playing in a career-low 40 games for the Jazz last season, Collins was traded to the Clippers where he appears to be slated as the starting power forward. The Clippers have a deep team, though, and Kawhi Leonard could shift to power forward in smaller ball lineups, so Collins' minutes could still be capped. Health is a question mark, with Collins having only played more than 68 games once since 2017-18, but when he's on the court the high-flying Collins makes a strong pick-and-roll/pop partner for James Harden and newly acquired Chris Paul. His per-minute production should be strong, but it isn't clear whether Collins will get typical starter minutes this season due to the quality depth in the Clippers' frontcourt.

Name: Jarrett Allen
2026 Outlook: Allen is a walking double-double with low-teens scoring on almost 70% shooting from both the field and the line with about a block and a steal per game. He is very consistent, and has the upside to ramp up his scoring into the mid-upper teens if needed, but like the rest of the Cavaliers starters he played his fewest minutes last season since joining the team because the unit is so strong. Either way, what Allen does provide is worthy of early-mid round consideration in fantasy leagues.

Name: Tyler Herro
2026 Outlook: Herro will miss the first month of the season, at least, after undergoing foot surgery in mid-late September. Herro was coming off a career season in which he set new personal bests in scoring, field goal percentage, assists, steals and 3-pointers per game as the Heat transitioned out of the Jimmy Butler era with Herro as the new perimeter offensive engine. He projects to continue to grow in that role this season, if and when he's healthy enough to return to full action. The Heat brought in shooter-scorers on the wing in Norman Powell and Andrew Wiggins, and start a lineup with two bigs that can shoot in Bam Adebayo and Kel'el Ware, so Herro should have space to operate and create as the lead guard in this lineup.

Name: Immanuel Quickley
2026 Outlook: Quickley has shown flashes of brilliance since being traded to the Raptors, but injuries have kept him off the court and limited his development. He played in only 33 games last season, with a three-season low of 27.8 MPG. Quickley will also have to contend with a new-look Raptors' starting lineup that features three other players with 20/5/5 upside. He is more lead guard than point guard anyway, but it's possible that his volume is capped with all the scorer-ballhandlers in the Raptors' lineup.

Name: Jrue Holiday
2026 Outlook: The Boston Celtics traded Holiday to the Portland Trail Blazers for Anfernee Simons and two second-round picks, saving $40M in luxury tax. Holiday, entering his 17th season, averaged 11.1 PPG, 4.3 RPG, and 3.9 APG in 30.6 MPG last season. Portland adds the veteran to mentor young guards Scoot Henderson and Shaedon Sharpe. Focused on winning, Holiday praised the team’s talent, Damian Lillard’s return, and Hall of Famer Chauncey Billups as coach, aiming to bring a culture of success. He could deliver similar stats this season.

Name: Nic Claxton
2026 Outlook: Claxton is only 26 years old, but he may already be too mature for the youth movement in Brooklyn. His minutes, and thus his numbers, were down across the board last season with 23-year old Day'Ron Sharpe and 21-year old Noah Clowney both playing larger roles. Add in Danny Wolf, a first round big man in this season's draft, and Claxton's minutes may decline for the third straight season, down from the 26.9 MPG he averaged last season. Claxton is a finisher on offense, a nightly double-double threat and a disruptive defender when he's on the court. Strong per-minute numbers, but if his minutes are down his volume will be as well.

Name: Draymond Green
2026 Outlook: Green remains the defensive anchor for the Warriors, even at age 35. Last season, he averaged 8.9 PPG, 6.3 RPG and 5.8 APG across 68 games while anchoring what was the league’s top defense after the All-Star break. Green’s defensive IQ allows him to guard multiple positions, serve as a secondary playmaker behind Stephen Curry, and run the Warriors’ offense. Though his 3-point shooting (32.5%) isn’t ideal, his presence on the floor is crucial. Green earned his ninth All-Defensive team selection last year, cementing his status as one of the league’s most impactful defenders. Green is a lower-middle/late round fantasy hoops prospect at this point in his career.

Name: Devin Vassell
2026 Outlook: Vassell was the second-leading scorer for the Spurs in 2023-24, but last season the team brought in All Star De'Aaron Fox and Rookie of the Year Stephon Castle. Then, this offseason, they spent the No. 2 overall pick on 6-7 combo guard Dylan Harper. Vassell still has plus shooter-scorer ability, but his scoring average had already dropped to a three-year low of 16.3 PPG last season. His role could diminish even further this season, making him a fringe top-100 prospect in fantasy leagues.

Name: Michael Porter Jr.
2026 Outlook: A 6-10 wing with excellent shooting ability, Porter is a pure natural scorer. He has been cast as the third option for the Nuggets, but with his offseason trade to Brooklyn he'll get the chance to sit in the first chair. While it isn't clear how Porter's efficiency will be affected without having Nikola Jokic to set him up, we have seen Porter's scoring increase dramatically for long stretches when Jamal Murray was out of the lineup. Also, after managing only 125 games through the first four seasons of his NBA career due to injury, Porter has played in 156 of a total of 164 possible games in the last two seasons. He could be in for a major scoring volume season with solid rebounds and excellent 3-point production.

Name: Malik Monk
2026 Outlook: Monk broke out last season, following up consecutive top-5 Sixth Man of the Year campaigns with a move into the starting lineup. In 45 games as a starter, Monk averaged 18.9 PPG, 6.5 APG and 4.0 RPG with 2.3 3PG. Monk is the nominal point guard for the Kings since De'Aaron Fox was traded, and he would have 20 PPG scoring potential if not for the Kings' plethora of perimeter scoring talent.

Name: Ace Bailey
2026 Outlook: The rookie is set to make an immediate impact for the rebuilding Jazz. At 6-6, 200 pounds, he combines scoring, court vision and defensive versatility, able to drive, shoot and guard multiple positions. Bailey has a chance to emerge as Utah’s second option behind Lauri Markkanen, contributing on both ends of the floor. Under Will Hardy’s system and with veteran guidance, he has the tools to become a key scorer and playmaker as the Jazz look to develop their young core.

Name: Keegan Murray
2026 Outlook: Murray has one of the purest 3-point shooting strokes in the NBA, but his percentage has dropped every season in the league, from 41.1 3FG% as a rookie to 34.3 3FG% last season. This could reflect that Murray is a more dynamic player now than he was when he entered the league, with fewer spot-up treys in the corner and more action off the dribble. Murray also has improved as a rebounder every season and averages near a steal and block per game to go with over two 3-pointers. In fact, Murray's best upside may be as a defender, since he plays in a lineup that already features so many strong talents on offense.

Name: Russell Westbrook
2026 Outlook: Westbrook, 36, remains unsigned as the 2025-26 season nears, but he’s on the cusp of league history. Needing just 506 points to surpass Oscar Robertson as the highest-scoring point guard ever, Westbrook also leads all-time in triple-doubles (203) and ranks eighth in assists (9,925). Last season with the Nuggets, he averaged 13.3 PPG, 6.1 APG, and 4.9 RPG in 27.9 MPG while recovering from hand surgery. A former MVP and two-time scoring champion, Westbrook’s veteran experience and scoring upside make him a potential bench contributor or waiver target in deeper leagues, especially if picked up by a contending team.

Name: Darius Garland
2026 Outlook: Garland is coming off a season in which he set new career-highs with 75 games played, 2.8 3PG and 47.2 FG% even though he, like the rest of the Cavaliers' starting five, played a career-low in minutes (30.7 MPG) because the overall unit was so strong. But Garland suffered a toe injury late last season, had offseason surgery and is expected to still be out recovering early in this campaign. When he returns, he likely returns to a very similar role and production as last season. But before last season he had never played 70 games in an NBA campaign, and it appears he will miss that games threshold again this season.

Name: Dyson Daniels
2026 Outlook: Daniels broke out last season, his first with the Hawks. He became a full-time starter and the best ballhawk in the league, leading the Association with 3.0 SPG. Daniels is developing into a strong 3-and-D option, knocking down 1.1 3PG last season. Add in 14.1 PPG, 5.9 RPG and 4.4 APG with 49.3 FG%, and Daniels is a strong across-the-boards producer outside of weak free throw shooting (61.4 FT% for his career).

Name: Cam Thomas
2026 Outlook: Thomas is in a contract year after signing a one-year qualifying offer this offseason. Already one of the purest backcourt scorers in the NBA who has increased his scoring average every season of his career up to 24.0 PPG in 2024-25, Thomas has the upside to go even bigger. Thomas is a bit undersized for a shooting guard at 6-3, so he should fit well next to new 6-8, do-everything rookie point guard Egor Demin. The big question with Thomas is health; he only played in 25 games last season and has never played in more than 67 in his four-year NBA career.

Name: Bradley Beal
2026 Outlook: Beal joins the Clippers after a rollercoaster stint with the Suns, where injuries limited him to 53 games each season. Known for his scoring (21.5 PPG in his career), he’ll likely provide consistent offensive production in Los Angeles, especially if he hits 60+ games. His main question mark is defense, though a fresh start alongside strong Clippers defenders could lead to modest improvement. Beal offers upside in points and 3-pointers but comes with durability risk. Best treated as a high-upside draft target or early-season waiver option depending on your league size if he stays healthy.

Name: Mark Williams
2026 Outlook: Williams enters his fourth NBA season as an elite per-minute producer with the game to play big minutes but a history of injury that has kept him off the court. Williams has only played in 106 of a possible 246 games in the NBA, meaning he has missed more action than he has played. He also averages only 23.7 MPG despite having started in 77 of those 106 games. But, per 36 minutes, he averages 18.7 points, 13.7 rebounds, 1.7 blocks and 1.0 steals on 62.2 FG% and 75.3 FT% for his career. Last season, he played 26.6 MPG, and averaged a 15 and 10 double-double. The Suns have had a hole in the middle for years that Williams could help fill, but only if he is able to stay healthy enough to be the full-time starter.

Name: Ausar Thompson
2026 Outlook: Thompson’s offense is still catching up to his elite defense, but he’s already one of fantasy’s most interesting category contributors. In just 22.5 MPG last season, the 22-year-old averaged 5.1 RPG, 2.3 APG, 1.7 SPG, and 0.7 BPG, elite defensive production for a wing. His 3-point shot remains a work in progress, but a full season of health and a more defined role under Detroit’s new coaching staff should unlock more minutes and counting stats. Thompson’s a solid redraft target from round 10 on for managers who value blocks, steals and efficient 2-point scoring.

Name: Ivica Zubac
2026 Outlook: Zubac was one of the breakout stars of the NBA last season. He had the dual accomplishment of turning in his best per-36 minute numbers as a Clipper (18.4 PP36, 13.9 RP36, 2.9 AP36) while simultaneously playing a career-high 32.8 MPG. The result was a massive leap in career-highs in all three categories and, in the midst of his peak athletic seasons at age 27, the likelihood that Zubac can follow that up with another strong effort this season. That said, the Clippers brought in two other strong center options this offseason in veterans Brook Lopez and John Collins, seemingly with the intent to help Zubac stay fresh. That could keep him from having to play as many minutes this season. Still, he enters this season as a top-50 fantasy prospect.

Name: Jimmy Butler III
2026 Outlook: The Warriors are a team that fits both Butler's strengths and his weaknesses as a player, allowing him to be a second option that isn't relied upon as heavily in the regular season with the upside for him to dust off "Playoffs Jimmy" once the postseason arrives. For fantasy purposes, Regular-Season Jimmy on the Warriors is a good player, but one with capped upside. He's more likely to average in the upper-teens of points per game than the 20s he averaged with the Heat. He also seems likely to miss games as he manages injury to get through the season. Butler hasn't played more than 65 games since 2016-17, and with his likely absences added into the projections it drops Butler to a mid/late-mid-round pick in fantasy leagues.

Name: Cameron Johnson
2026 Outlook: Johnson is an elite 3-point shooter from the frontcourt, coming off a season where he notched career highs of 18.8 PPG, 2.8 3PG, 47.5 FG% and 89.3 FT%. But while that scoring average is very similar to that of Michael Porter Jr., the player he was traded for this offseason, Johnson is likely to average fewer points when he gets to Denver. Because while Johnson was a primary option for the Nets, he'll be one of several similar or greater scoring threats for the Nuggets. He should get more, better 3-point shooting opportunities in Denver playing off Nikola Jokic, but his overall volume likely drops. This makes him more fantasy flex option than positional starter this season.

Name: Isaiah Hartenstein
2026 Outlook: Hartenstein became a full-time starter for the first time in his career last season, averaging career-highs in minutes, points, rebounds, assists and blocks in his first campaign with the Thunder. He is a hustle, double-double player that fits perfectly cleaning up around the rim for finishes and put-backs against imbalanced defenses selling out to stop Shai Gilgeous-Alexander and the rest of the elite Thunder offense. His role and production are likely to be similar again this season.

Name: Alex Sarr
2026 Outlook: Sarr was considered one of the most talented members of the 2024 NBA draft class but a player that may need more time to develop. Sarr was more polished than expected as a rookie, flirting with nightly double-double status while also notching 1.6 3PG, 1.5 BPG and 0.7 SPG. The strong production in these unique categories gives Sarr solid upside in category leagues, and he has the achievable upside to potentially average a double-double with more scoring this season. One question mark is Sarr's health after he injured his calf playing in Eurobasket this summer, but he is expected to be able to return in time for the NBA season.

Name: Payton Pritchard
2026 Outlook: Pritchard is the reigning NBA Sixth Man of the Year after setting new career-bests in scoring, assists, rebounds, 3-pointers and steals per game. With Jayson Tatum injured and Jrue Holiday traded away, Pritchard could play an even larger role this season. Even coming off the bench, Pritchard should get near-starter minutes in 2025-26.

Name: Egor Demin
2026 Outlook: Demin appears set to open the season as Brooklyn’s starting point guard after a strong Summer League showing. The 6-9 rookie has rare size and playmaking ability but comes with questions about turnovers and shooting consistency. Encouragingly, he hit 43.5% of his 3s on high volume during the Summer League, suggesting early upside if the shot holds. Demin’s fantasy value will hinge on his ability to handle starter minutes while limiting turnovers, and he’s a late-round flier with streaming appeal for assists.

Name: Tyus Jones
2026 Outlook: Jones signed a one-year deal with the Magic, where he’ll likely run the offense for a young Magic team that badly needed a true floor general. Jones remains one of the most efficient point guards in the league, leading the league in assist-to-turnover ratio for six straight seasons (including a record 7.35 in 2023-24). He averaged 10.2 PPG, 5.3 APG, and shot 41.4% from three with the Suns last year. While Jones’ scoring ceiling is modest, his elite efficiency, steady playmaking and excellent percentages make him a sneaky fantasy value in most leagues.

Name: Brandin Podziemski
2026 Outlook: Podziemski enters his third season as the frontrunner to be named the Warriors’ starting shooting guard. He thrived post-All-Star break, averaging 15.5 PPG, 5.9 RPG and 3.7 APG while shooting 46.5% from the field and 43.8% from deep. His role is safe for now, with De’Anthony Melton expected to be eased back from injury and Buddy Hield likely the main competition for production. Podziemski offers steady scoring, elite shooting percentages and sneaky playmaking and rebounding. He is a great late-round fantasy target with room to grow.

Name: Santi Aldama
2026 Outlook: Aldama broke out last season with new career bests in five of the six fantasy hoops counting categories, excepting only blocked shots. He backs up every frontcourt position for the Grizzlies, but also gets spot starts in cases of injury. With Jaren Jackson Jr. questionable to start the season due to turf toe, Aldama could get some starts early on. Aldama is a stretch big with double-double potential and two 3-pointers per game when he gets minutes. He is a fringe top-100 fantasy hoops prospect with upside to deliver top-75 production when he moves into the starting lineup.

Name: Stephon Castle
2026 Outlook: Castle finished his rookie season strong, taking advantage of an increased role with Victor Wembanyama and De'Aaron Fox both out the last month-plus to average 19 points, 6 assists and 5 boards in his last 18 games. On one hand, Castle's role should be much smaller than that with everyone healthy this season. On the other, he is still only 20 years old, an incredible athlete with a knack for drawing fouls with major potential to thrive if his jump shot improves. He currently projects as a starter in his sophomore campaign, making him a fringe top-100 fantasy prospect with a ton of upside.

Name: Shaedon Sharpe
2026 Outlook: Sharpe was widely considered one of the most talented players in the 2022 NBA draft class, but he was very raw with little experience beyond high school when he was drafted. He has improved consistently when healthy, and is coming off a campaign where he set new career bests in scoring and 3-point volume even though his minutes decreased from his second season. The Trail Blazers traded away leading scorer Anfernee Simons this offseason and replaced him with a lower volume scorer in Jrue Holiday, meaning Sharpe should have more scoring responsibility this season.

Name: Zach Edey
2026 Outlook: Edey enters his second season as Memphis’ starting center after earning All-Rookie First Team honors and finishing fifth in Rookie of the Year voting. He averaged 9.2 PPG, 8.3 RPG and 1.3 BPG in just 21.5 MPG, leading all rookies in FG% (58.0%). The Grizzlies need him to become a bigger scoring threat, especially in the post, to complement Ja Morant and Jaren Jackson Jr. He’ll miss the start of 2025-26 following ankle surgery but remains a key component of Memphis’ rotation once healthy, making him a big man worth stashing.

Name: Toumani Camara
2026 Outlook: Camara enters his third NBA season with the Portland Trail Blazers, likely locked into a starting role after showing growth in his second season. He averaged 11.3 PPG, 5.8 RPG, 2.2 APG and 1.5 SPG while improving his 3-point shooting and off-ball play. Defensively, Camara’s become a reliable multi-position stopper, earning the trust of coaches and the front office. Upside lies in steady counting stats and strong defensive contributions, though limited usage may cap scoring bursts. For fantasy purposes, Camara is a solid waiver or deep-draft target in leagues that reward steals and defensive stats.

Name: Isaiah Collier
2026 Outlook: Collier enters his second season with a clear opportunity after the Jazz moved on from Collin Sexton and Jordan Clarkson. The 29th overall pick in 2024 averaged 8.7 PPG and 6.3 APG as a rookie but struggled with efficiency, shooting just 25% from beyond the arc. Collier’s starting job isn’t guaranteed, with rookie first-rounder Walter Clayton Jr. potentially pushing for minutes, but he should see heavy run early as the Jazz evaluates its young backcourt. Collier’s a late-round stash in most leagues, with value tied to assists and potential growth as a shooter.

Name: Scotty Pippen Jr.
2026 Outlook: Pippen is a reserve player that has proven he can return starter production when Ja Morant is out. In 30 games without Morant, he averaged 13.0 PPG, 5.8 APG, 4.3 RPG, 1.6 SPG and 1.3 3PG while shooting 50.9% from the field. But when Morant is healthy, Pippen's production is limited to non-fantasy starter numbers. Pippen could have more opportunity to get on the court at shooting guard with Desmond Bane traded away, and could also be part of a strong guard duo off the bench next to scoring point Ty Jerome. He is a fringe top-100 fantasy prospect, with upside to deliver top-75 production when he moves into the starting lineup.

Name: Bennedict Mathurin
2026 Outlook: Mathurin enters this season as Pacers’s top scoring option with Tyrese Haliburton sidelined for the year. The 23-year-old swingman averaged 16.1 PPG, 5.3 RPG and 1.9 APG in 72 regular-season games last season and showed he can rise in the playoffs, including 23 points and 13 rebounds in Game 7 of the Finals. Mathurin’s physicality and ability to get to the free throw line give him upside as a primary scorer. Expect him to push for 20.0 PPG, making him a great late-round target.

Name: Aaron Nesmith
2026 Outlook: Nesmith has quietly become one of the league’s best 3-and-D wings. Last season, he averaged 12.0 PPG and 4.0 RPG on elite shooting splits (50%/43%/91%) despite missing time with an ankle injury. Nesmith was huge in the Pacers’ playoff run, including a 30-point explosion against the Knicks and shooting nearly 50% from deep across 23 postseason games. His role could expand with Tyrese Haliburton sidelined. Nesmith is a steady source of 3-pointers and defensive stats with occasional scoring upside, making him best used as a streamer.

Name: Yves Missi
2026 Outlook: Missi had a solid rookie season, earning All-Rookie second team honors, but he faces a tough battle to retain the Pelicans’ starting center spot. Defensive rebounding remains a major concern and defensive awareness in pick-and-rolls needs improvement. While efficient at the rim last year (54.7% FG), inconsistent finishing and a shaky Summer League showing leave questions. Kevon Looney’s experience and rebounding prowess make him a safer option, so Missi must impress in training camp to start.

Name: Kyrie Irving
2026 Outlook: Irving tore his ACL in March but is reportedly ahead of schedule in his recovery. The Mavericks won’t rush him, but a return sometime after New Year’s still looks possible. Irving averaged 24.7 PPG, 4.6 APG and shot 40.1% from deep last season, so he’s worth stashing in leagues with IR spots, especially if you can afford to wait. When he returns, he’ll likely replace D’Angelo Russell in the starting lineup and immediately have top-40 fantasy upside.

Name: Jared McCain
2026 Outlook: McCain was a revelation in his rookie season, averaging 15.3 points on 38.3% from 3-point range before a meniscus injury ended things after just 23 games. He often looked like one of the 76ers’ best players on the floor, holding his own alongside Joel Embiid, Tyrese Maxey and Paul George. Now heading into his second season, McCain is coming off surgery for a meniscus tear and also suffered a torn UCL in his right thumb during an offseason workout, putting his availability for the start of the season in doubt. When healthy, he’ll provide shooting and serve as a secondary playmaker. His role may range from sixth man to starter depending on team health.

Name: Obi Toppin
2026 Outlook: Toppin is expected to have an expanded role following Myles Turner’s departure. The 27-year-old averaged a career-high 10.5 PPG and 4.0 RPG in 79 games while making 110 3-pointers. His versatility allows him to play small-ball center in key lineups, and he consistently sparks momentum with highlight-reel plays. Toppin’s durability and transition scoring make him a reliable contributor. While his ceiling is modest compared with the Pacers’ top stars, expect him to provide steady fantasy value as a solid waiver or bench option.

Name: Cam Whitmore
2026 Outlook: Whitmore joins the Wizards in 2025-26 hoping for a fresh start and more opportunity to showcase his scoring upside. A former first-round pick, Whitmore is a natural slasher and bucket-getter, averaging 23.1 points per 40 minutes. Washington’s thin frontcourt could give him major minutes, though he might play power forward instead of his natural small forward spot. The key for Whitmore is to round out his game, improve his passing and embrace defense.

Name: Fred VanVleet
2026 Outlook: VanVleet tore his ACL and is expected to miss the season.

Name: Ty Jerome
2026 Outlook: Jerome joined the Grizzlies on a three-year deal over the summer and is expected to help fill the shooting void left by Desmond Bane and Luke Kennard. Last season with the Cavaliers, he averaged 12.5 PPG, 3.4 APG, and shot 43.9% from beyond the arc in 19.9 MPG, thriving as a sixth man and elite floor spacer. If he sees consistent bench minutes and an uptick in shot volume, he could be a strong value, but Jerome has limited defensive impact and has to adjust to his new team. Jerome is best viewed as a streaming option with upside as a scorer and 3-point shooter.

Name: Aaron Wiggins
2026 Outlook: Wiggins has emerged as one of the Thunder’s top bench players. Last season, he averaged 12.0 PPG in 22.9 MPG, shooting 48.8% from the field and 38.3% from three on career-high 4.5 attempts per game. A slick scorer and capable cutter, Wiggins excels as a microwave scorer off the bench. To elevate his fantasy impact this season, he’ll need to maintain his outside shooting, stay a double-digit scorer and continue improving his point-of-attack defense.

Name: Neemias Queta
2026 Outlook: Queta enters the season poised for a larger role with the Celtics after an impressive EuroBasket, where he averaged 15.5 PPG, 8 RPG and 1.7 BPG. Last NBA season, he showed elite screening, solid rim protection and above-average offensive rebounding while contributing as a reliable lob target and pick-and-roll finisher. Queta must improve defensive strength, post defense and decision-making on putbacks, while maintaining floor spacing and continuing to develop his mid-range and floater scoring to maximize his fantasy impact.
